<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: INTERNATIONAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 U.S., Japan Expand Scope of Trade Talks: The two nations agreed to include 
banking and other financial services in negotiations aimed at opening Japanese 
markets to more American goods. U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor said 
the trading partners, at a Paris meeting of the 25-nation Organization for 
Economic Cooperation and Development, also decided to talk about how to ensure 
protection of copyrights, patents and other intellectual property rights. The 
new discussion areas will be part of so-called framework talks aimed at 
improving U.S. access to Japan's tightly controlled markets. The original 
areas, still under negotiation, are autos and auto parts, medical equipment, 
telecommunications products and insurance. 
</P>
