<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE FAMILY FILE: 90'S FAMILY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Items are compiled from Times staff and news services. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Teen-Agers Staying Virgins Longer Than We Thought 
</P>
<P>
 Boys and girls are staying virgins longer than most adults think, according to 
a new report. 
</P>
<P>
 The Alan Guttmacher Institute said Monday that 62% of adults assume the 
average teen-ager has sex before turning 16. But 70% of all boys and girls are 
still virgins when they reach 16, and 18% abstain until at least their 20th 
birthday, the institute said. 
</P>
<P>
 Among girls who do have sex before 15, 60% said they were raped or coerced in 
some unspecified manner, the institute said, quoting a 1987 study. 
</P>
<P>
 Teen sex "is not as widespread, and does not begin as early, as most adults 
believe," the report said. 
</P>
<P>
 The institute, which studies reproductive issues and is affiliated with 
Planned Parenthood, based its report on research it primarily conducted in the 
1990s and the research of others. 
</P>
<P>
 Among other findings: 
</P>
<P>
 * Two-thirds of today's sexually active teens used some type of contraception 
the first time they had sex, and at least 70% use contraception regularly. 
</P>
<P>
 * Adolescents account for 30% of out-of-wedlock births today, compared to 50% 
in 1970. Nail Polish Ranks No. 1 With Young Cosmetics Users 
</P>
<P>
 Fingernails are important to teen-age girls, judging by how much nail polish 
they use. Simmons Market Research Bureau surveyed 3,000 teen-agers and found 
that nail polish was their favorite cosmetic, with 71.6% of the young women 
saying they used it. Lipstick was a close second, used by 66.9 %, followed by 
mascara at 59.9%, eye shadow at 54.5% and blush at 49.9%. 
</P>
<P>
 The survey also found working teen-agers are more likely to use mascara, blush 
and foundation makeup than those who don't work -- an indication that at an 
early age, women understand the importance of making a good impression on the 
job. Popular 'Power Rangers' Make Their Way to Kids Books 
</P>
<P>
 Grosset & Dunlap has published four chapter books for kids 6 to 11 years of 
age based on the popular TV program, "The Mighty Morphin Power Rangers." The 
titles are "It's Morphin Time!" by William McCay, "Megazord to the Rescue!" by 
Cathy East Dubowski, "The Terror Toad" by Jean Waricha and "Rita's Revenge" by 
Rusty Hallock. Each book costs $3.95. 
</P>
<P>
 * Family File appears Wednesdays on the '90s Family page. 
</P>
</TEXT>
